Join the Northcoast Chapter of the CA Native Plant Society tomorrow for a Mt. Rainier Wildflower Adventure webinar at 7:00 pm!

On Wednesday, September 9th, Donna Wildearth will talk about her journey to see the sub-alpine wildflowers on Mt. Rainier, which John Muir referred to as ". . . the most luxurious and the most extravagantly beautiful of all the alpine gardens I ever beheld in all my mountain-top ramblings." With her and Kathy Dilley's photos and informative comment, Donna will recount their trip last year to see this wildflower spectacle.

Happy Labor Day! No School on Monday!

Labor Day is a federal holiday in the United States celebrated on the first Monday in September to honor and recognize the American labor movement and the works and contributions of laborers to the development and achievements of the United States. It is the Monday of the long weekend known as Labor Day Weekend.

Beginning in the late 19th century, as the trade union and labor movements grew, trade unionists proposed that a day be set aside to celebrate labor. "Labor Day" was promoted by the Central Labor Union and the Knights of Labor, which organized the first parade in New York City. In 1887, Oregon was the first state of the United States to make it an official public holiday. By the time it became an official federal holiday in 1894, thirty states in the United States officially celebrated Labor Day.
-- Wikipedia

The City of Rio Dell needs your support to build a bike trail along the Eel River! By signing their petition, you increase their chances of receiving vital grant funding!

Rio Dell currently lacks dedicated non-motorized paths along the Eel River for pedestrians and bicyclists to enjoy and experience the beautiful environment of this area. A proposal exists to create a segment of the new "Great Redwood Trail" along the banks of the Eel River through Rio Dell and create opportunities to exercise, experience nature and learn about the Eel River. The City of Rio Dell needs your help to make this happen! Please sign the petition today!

This Saturday, September 5, is Free Fishing Day in California!

The last chance of the year to fish for free arrives over the Labor Day holiday weekend. Free Fishing Day is being offered by the California Department of Fish and Wildlife (CDFW) on Saturday, Sept. 5.

“Free Fishing Day is the perfect chance to see what so many Californians already have discovered: That fishing can be a great escape in difficult times and does wonders to invigorate physical health and restore mental well-being,” said CDFW Director Charlton H. Bonham.

"Look, Listen and Learn" produces children’s television to bridge the achievement gap so that BIPOC (Black, Indigenous, and People of Color) kids start school ready to learn and able to succeed!

Episodes are available on the LL&L website and YouTube channel!

Longtime TV producer and host Val Thomas-Matson is the creative force behind “Look, Listen and Learn,” a new community-powered TV series (which airs on YouTube) designed to encourage BIPOC children to take their rightful place in the world. She anchors each episode as Auntie Lena, an ultra-reassuring character who dialogues with a sweet-tempered puppet friend named Possum to explore the meaning of core developmental preoccupations of childhood (e.g., making friends, coping with change) — as well as far more difficult concepts to grasp, such as the COVID-19 pandemic and the Black Lives Matter movement.

Episodes available on the website include Practicing Courage, What Does "Black Lives Matter" Mean?, The Community Garden, and more!

https://www.looklistenandlearn.org/watch-now

Register now to participate in the fifth annual 2020 Walk to End Alzheimer’s on Saturday, October 10!

The Alzheimer’s Association is inviting Humboldt County residents to join the fight to end Alzheimer’s by participating in the 5th annual Alzheimer’s Association Walk to End Alzheimer’s® on October 10. There is no cost to register and no limit on the size of your team. Register at: https://act.alz.org/site/TR;jsessionid=00000000.app201a?fr_id=13298&pg=entry&NONCE_TOKEN=6B441D12EE7C660D4E70DB0A22D1CED8

From the Walk website:
"The world may look a little different right now, but one thing hasn’t changed: our commitment to ending Alzheimer’s. This year, Walk to End Alzheimer’s® is everywhere — on every sidewalk, track and trail. Your health and safety are our top priorities. This year’s event won’t be a large in-person gathering — instead, we invite you to walk in small teams of friends and family while others in your community do the same. Because we are all still walking and fundraising for the same thing: a world without Alzheimer’s and all other dementia."

Not sure what vegetables to plant in your garden this fall? Want to improve the health of your houseplants or learn more about pest management? A University of California Cooperative Extension Master Gardener can help!

View the UC Master Gardener Program of Humboldt and Del Norte Counties website to reach the Help Desk and access free recorded classes and other resources! The online library includes presentations such as “Vegetable Garden Basics”, “Heather Growing and Landscape Design”, “Reducing the Vulnerability of Buildings to Wildfires”, etc.

Since 1988, well over 1,000 residents of Humboldt and Del Norte have participated in the Master Gardener Program’s certificate training!

https://ucanr.edu/sites/hdnmastergardeners/

Check out the Art on the Fence installation by the Arcata ballpark!

Playhouse Arts and JustArts present ART ON THE FENCE, an outdoor exhibition of BIPOC and White Community Artists, putting down paint in times of change. -- Laura Muñoz, Project Coordinator

As part of the Round Story, a multi-year project which uses the arts to encourage dialogues about racial equity, social justice and our changing demographics, Art on the Fence is an inclusive expression of different voices and experiences. The works are done on plywood panels 4×5 and 5×5 and are hanging on the fence by the Arcata Ballpark, 888 F Street.

More information including artist statements and photos of the artwork can be found on the Arcata Playhouse website at https://www.arcataplayhouse.org/2020/08/11/art-on-the-fence/

NOW HIRING:
Director of Extended Student Programs!

Full-time, year-round position – to start as soon as possible!

Deadline to apply: September 10 at 3:00 pm

JOB SUMMARY:
Under the direction of the Superintendent and in coordination with site Principals, the Director of Extended Student Programs is responsible for the overall development and management of the District’s extended student programs (i.e. after school program, before school program, vacation day camps, pre-school, and enrichment programs).

MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS:
Bachelor’s Degree and/or experience in child development, education, recreation, or a related field. Prior management and/or supervisorial experience in areas of extended student programs (i.e. childcare after-school programs) of not less than five (5) years.

COMPENSATION:
Annual salary starting at $53,643.96 depending on experience, with health and retirement benefits.

post_text:
National Relaxation Day is Saturday, August 15th!

Let National Relaxation Day encourage you to slow down and unwind! It's a day to focus on taking care of ourselves by taking a moment to relax. National Relaxation Day is an important day as we all need a break from the fast-paced and often hectic lifestyles we live. On this holiday, people are encouraged to engage in activities that not only rest their bodies but also their minds as well.

Although a certain amount of stress is normal, too much of it can be harmful to your physical and mental health. Take care of yourself today. Read a book, watch a movie, take a nap, or go for a long walk. Studies have even shown that going on a walk a few times a week leads to improved well-being and lower stress levels! No matter what you choose to do, just remember to take it easy, even if it’s only for a few minutes. Happy National Relaxation Day!

Snapshot HumCoast BioBlitz 2020 starts Monday, August 17!

Calling all beachgoers! Your eyes and your smart phones are needed to gather observations for the BioBlitz taking place August 17-31!

A BioBlitz is a community science effort to collect and share data on plant and animal species within a defined area and time period. This effort is a collaboration of local organizations seeking to create a snapshot in time of species observed along the Humboldt County coast over a two-week period. Join in and add to the data compiled!

No expertise of local plant or animal species is required!

Find more information on the Northcoast Environmental Center website at https://www.yournec.org/snapshot-humcoast-bioblitz-2020-august-17-31/#

Mark your calendars for Humboldt State University's free annual Campus & Community Dialogue on Race - October 26-30, with virtual presentation by Claudia Rankine on November 7!

This year's theme is Global Justice for Black Lives: Examining the Past and Reimagining the Future.

The Campus & Community Dialogue on Race (CDOR) is an annual event at Humboldt State University that invites students, staff, faculty, administrators, and community members to present and attend programs that relate to racial justice and its intersections with all forms of oppression and resistance.

The vision of Campus & Community Dialogue on Race is to achieve racial, social, and environmental justice. The program's mission is to promote and facilitate social and environmental change by engaging a diverse range of individuals, communities, and viewpoints to explore the impact of racism and its intersections with all forms of oppression.

https://dialogue.humboldt.edu/

Firewood vouchers for low to moderate income seniors will be available starting August 17!

Low-cost firewood vouchers will be sold starting August 17, 2020 by the Humboldt Senior Resource Center (HSRC). Households with an individual 55 or older and living on a low to moderate income are eligible to purchase one firewood voucher.

Vouchers are priced on a sliding scale costing between $100-150 (tax included in the fee) based upon the purchaser’s household size and monthly household income. Once purchased, the voucher can be redeemed for one cord of wood at the Humboldt County Sheriff’s Work Alternative Program (SWAP) lot in Eureka starting on August 29, 2020.

Find out more at http://www.humsenior.org/programs/activities-programs/summer-2020-senior-firewood-sales/

Webinar "Pathways to Parks - Youth Access for Health and Wellness" is tomorrow, August 6, at 11:00 am!

After months of navigating uncharted waters, millions of California families are grappling with the reality that life will not return to normal this Fall. Yet with great challenge comes great opportunity. On Thursday August 6, join California State Parks Foundation and California's First Partner Jennifer Siebel Newsom as we explore solutions for a brighter path forward. We will hear directly from youth and nonprofit leaders about opportunities to create greater equity in this moment and to chart new Pathways to Parks.

Panelists include:
- Jennifer Siebel Newsom, California’s First Partner
- Holly Martinez, Director of Programs & Advocacy, California State Parks Foundation
- Lesford Duncan, Senior Director of Programs, Outdoor Outreach
- Santos Plaza, Youth Field Instructor, Outdoor Outreach
- Kim Moore Bailey, CEO, Youth Outside

To register: https://us02web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_MsENoWx2QqCTJvBUoNF8TA

"The Artistry of Black Organizing in the 21st Century" - an online conversation tomorrow at 2:00-3:30 pm!

Sponsored by Haymarket Books, and independent, nonprofit publisher. This event is FREE, with donations gratefully accepted.

WHEN: Tuesday, August 4, 2:00-3:30 pm

WHERE: Register through Eventbrite to receive a link to the video conference.

SPEAKERS:
Mary Hooks is the co-director of Southerners on New Ground (SONG). SONG is a political home for LGBTQ liberation across all lines of race, class, abilities, age, culture, gender, and sexuality in the South.

Monica Simpson is the Executive Director of SisterSong, the National Women of Color Reproductive Justice Collective.

Toni-Michelle Williams is an auto-theorist, performance artist, and executive director of Solutions Not Punishment Collaborative (SNAPCO).

Tiffany Lethabo King is an associate professor of Women’s, Gender and Sexuality Studies at Georgia State University.

Join community members in the Valley West neighborhood for Socially Distant Clean the Sidewalk Days this Sunday, August 2!

WHEN: Sunday, August 2, 9:00-11:00 am

WHERE: Meet at Valley West Park on Hallen Drive. If you have questions, or have trouble finding the group day-of, please text or call 707-601-4247.

Join community members in the Valley West neighborhood for Socially Distant Clean the Sidewalk Days on the first Sunday of every month! Participants of all ages are welcome to attend, and work will include picking up non-hazardous items left behind in the neighborhood's public spaces. Participants are encouraged to dress for the weather and to bring water. Gloves, hand sanitizer, and all necessary cleanup tools will be provided, and participants are welcome to bring their own supplies if preferred. Volunteers must bring their own facial coverings, and social distancing best practices and will be enforced. Volunteers will also be expected to sign day volunteer agreements and COVID-19 liability waivers.

THANK YOU to our incredible Food Service staff members who have been serving an average of 374 meals per day, Monday-Friday, through our Children’s Summer Meals Program!

We are very grateful to have such dedicated staff members! They have been working since school closed in March to offer children meals five days a week all spring and summer!

Julie Nichols and Adrienne Arnold have taken turns being the Head Cook heroes, creating nutritious and delicious meals and helping create menus. Nora Lovell has been filling in as Assistant Cook, while Grace Lovell has worked as a substitute to help out the team.

Grace Lovell also made child-size face masks along with Susana Flores-Delgado, which were distributed for free to kids coming for meals!

Melanie Dawson is our Mobile Meal Hero. She leaves Arcata Elementary with the van full of breakfast and lunch meal bags and distributes the meals to the six mobile sites. She knows the families and provides a consistent happy presence for the children.

WE APPRECIATE OUR FOOD SERVICE HEROES SO MUCH!

Submissions open on July 25 and close on August 2.

10 Reasons to Read to Older Kids:

Every parent knows that it's good to read to kids when they're little. It helps babies, toddlers, and preschoolers develop spoken language, recognize letters and words, and get ready for kindergarten. But it's actually beneficial to read to kids even after they can read on their own. Research shows that continued reading aloud after age 5 (and well beyond) improves reading and listening skills, as well as academic performance (and it is also loads of fun!).

Continue reading this article on the ParentMap website at https://www.parentmap.com/article/benefits-of-reading-aloud-to-big-kids?utm_source=newsletter&utm_medium=email&utm_content=read-big-kids-more&utm_campaign=parentmap-themed-cleverwaystoconnect-07-15-2020

National Moth Week is July 18-26!

National Moth Week celebrates the beauty, life cycles, and habitats of moths. “Moth-ers” of all ages and abilities are encouraged to learn about, observe, and document moths in their backyards, parks, and neighborhoods.

National Moth Week is being held, worldwide, during the last full week of July. NMW offers everyone, everywhere a unique opportunity to become a Citizen Scientist and contribute scientific data about moths. Through partnerships with major online biological data depositories, NMW participants can help map moth distribution and provide needed information on other life history aspects around the globe.

http://nationalmothweek.org/

Through partnerships with major online biological data depositories, NMW participants can help map moth distribution and provide needed information on other life history aspects around the globe.

http://nationalmothweek.org/

Malala graduated from Oxford University!

22-year-old Nobel Peace Prize laureate Malala Yousafzai has graduated from Oxford University! The world-famous girls' education advocate, who survived an assassination attempt by the Taliban eight years ago, shared her good news on Twitter, posting pictures from the celebration which included a "trashing," an Oxford tradition in which new graduates are covered with foam, confetti, and food. She wrote that it's "hard to express my joy and gratitude right now as I completed my Philosophy, Politics and Economics degree at Oxford."

This Saturday, July 18, is Nelson Mandela International Day!

“It is easy to break down and destroy. The heroes are those who make peace and build.” - Nelson Mandela

On July 18 every year, the United Nations invites you to mark Nelson Mandela International Day by making a difference in your communities. Everyone has the ability and the responsibility to change the world for the better! Mandela Day is an occasion for all to take action and inspire change.

Nelson Mandela devoted his life to the service of humanity — as a human rights lawyer, a prisoner of conscience, an international peacemaker, and the first democratically elected president of a free South Africa.

https://www.un.org/en/events/mandeladay/

The online application deadline for the Pandemic EBT card is tomorrow, July 15!

Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families may get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most will get their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May.

Families with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals and who do not get their P-EBT card in the mail by the end of May must apply online before July 15, 2020.

The online application is available (in English, Spanish, and Chinese) at https://www.cdss.ca.gov/home/pandemic-ebt

Black Minds Matter: A free, five-part online series starting July 16!

Black Minds Matter was designed as a free, public course to draw parallels between the violence facing Black Lives in policing and the symbolic violence facing Black Minds in schools, colleges, and universities.

In 2017, the first Black Minds Matter course was offered in response to the killing of Alfred Olango in San Diego. As with Michael Brown, Tamir Rice, Eric Garner, Sandra Bland and many others, Alfred was unarmed and killed by law enforcement officers.

In the wake of the murders of George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Tony McDade, Ahmaud Arbery and others, we received numerous requests to offer the course again. This time, Black Minds Matter will include two co-hosts – Dr. Luke Wood (returning) and Dr. Donna Y. Ford (new). Each course will open with commentary from Drs. Wood and Ford and then introduce guest speakers and interviewees who will discuss their perspectives on the education of Black students at all levels of education.

https://jlukewood.com/black-minds-matter/

post_text:
Freedom Reads: Anti-Bias Book Talk Series by Teaching for Change

Teaching for Change associate director Allyson Criner Brown is producing the series for parents, teachers, and librarians. She explains, “Freedom Reads: Anti-Bias Book Talk is part anti-bias training, part book review. Each short segment explores anti-bias books for home and the classroom with the goal to strengthen parents’ and teachers’ anti-bias, anti-racism lens and their ability to critically analyze children’s media.”

Designed with parents in mind, episodes run under ten minutes and each one walks viewers through a synopsis of the book, relevant resources, and four to five key points from an anti-bias, critical literacy lens. Freedom Reads is appropriate for parents, caregivers, and educators.

https://socialjusticebooks.org/freedom-reads/

Enjoy watching birds from home? Did you know that birdwatching is a gateway to a powerful mindfulness practice? It’s called a “bird sit.”

A bird sit is like an outdoor meditation with a focus on birds.
Bird sits provide similar benefits to mindfulness practices, including relaxation and quiet mind. They also reveal the birds’ secret language.

What secrets will the birds reveal to you?

Free online restorative movement classes Tuesdays and Thursdays!

Restorative movement is for people of all ages, and is helpful for developing balance and bone strength, and managing stress. Class includes breathwork, relaxation, and a variety of yoga and non-yoga movement styles.

Email or call instructor Ann Constantino – see website for contact information.

Arcata Playhouse announces its Summer Youth Arts Program!

To continue to build community through the arts during these isolated times, the Arcata Playhouse presents the "Playhouse Wonder Wagon", a mobile art service! Coming to local elementary school and community centers parking lots near you!

The Playhouse Wonder Wagon will deliver free art packets to community pods of kids of all ages with materials for craft and dance the week of July 6th - July 11th.

The Playhouse hopes this is the first of many weeks of the Playhouse Wonder Wagon summer services! Supplies, and instructions will be delivered on Monday, July 6th, Tuesday, July 7th, and Wednesday July 8th at various locations including Valley West, Pacific Union Elementary, and Redwood Coast Montessori (check the schedule on their website). A physically distanced parade will be held in the Creamery District on Saturday, July 11th.

Physical distancing and COVID masks will be required for all Playhouse Wonder Wagon activities.

https://www.arcataplayhouse.org/2020/06/22/playhouse-wonder-wagon/

post_text:
HAPPY FATHER’S DAY!

Sunday, June 21 is Father’s Day! Mrs. Sonora Smart Dodd is credited for being the one to popularize this special day, starting events that led to Father’s Day becoming a U.S. national holiday. Her story began as she sat listening to a Mother’s Day sermon in 1909. Mrs. Dodd thought that it might be nice to honor fathers as well. Her father, William Smart, had raised his six children alone on his farm in Washington after his wife died giving birth.

Mrs. Dodd proposed to the Spokane Ministerial Association and the YMCA that they celebrate a “father’s day.” She chose the 5th of June because it was her father’s birthday.

The idea received strong support, but the ministers of Spokane asked that the day be changed to give them extra time to prepare sermons on the unexplored subject of fathers. The first Father’s Day in Spokane, Washington, was observed on June 19, 1910 (the third Sunday in June), and became an annual event there. Soon, other towns had their own celebrations.
- from The Old Famer’s Almanac website

Watch Your Words: How to Support People with Mental Health Conditions

Being mindful of language is one simple thing we can do to support those with mental health conditions, and to decrease the associated stigma. As Barria says, “You never know what someone else is going through, so those topics that are super serious and intimate should not be joked about. In my ideal world, when people hear a joke or a comment about wanting to kill yourself or about the ‘loony bin’ or the ‘funny farm,’ people will stand up and say, ‘That’s not okay.’”

https://www.parentmap.com/article/words-support-mental-health

post_text:
7 Ways to Help Your Daughter Love Her Body

One of the most freeing feelings in the world is loving yourself just as you are — but in a world where girls are constantly bombarded with messages about what their bodies should look like, raising them to be body positive can feel like an impossible task. A study by the Girl Scouts found that 80% of 10-year-old girls are afraid of getting fat, and other studies have found that 85% of women and 79% of girls have opted out of activities due to a lack of body confidence. With kids and teens being exposed to narrow standards of beauty in media, marketing, and online, many adults may wonder what they can do to turn the tide.

https://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=25273&utm_source=newsletter&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=20200615&ts=20200615

post_text:
Sunday is Flag Day!

Flag Day is celebrated on June 14 each year, and commemorates the adoption of the Stars and Stripes as the official flag of the United States. It is a day to celebrate and show respect for our flag and its designers and makers.

In 1775, the first American flag, called the Continental colors, was created for our fledgling country - but it looked too similar to the British flag. So, on June 14, 1777, the Second Continental Congress passed a resolution that “the flag of the United States be 13 stripes, alternate red and white,” and that “the union be 13 stars, white in a blue field, representing a new constellation."

It wasn't until 1916, that President Woodrow Wilson issued an official decree making June 14th Flag Day. However, some say the original Flag Day occurred in Wisconsin in 1885, and that Bernard J. Cigrand, a school teacher, began the practice of celebrating the flag’s birthday. He assigned his class to write essays about the flag and its significance.

Read more: https://militarybenefits.info/flag-day/

Seeking community members for the District's Citizens' Oversight Committee!

The Arcata Elementary School District is accepting applications from interested individuals to serve on the Citizens’ Oversight Committee to oversee expenditures of bond funds and parcel tax funds. The Committee consists of seven members who meet at least one time per year to review and report on expenditures of funds to ensure money is used only for voter-approved purposes.

Some Committee members may live outside District boundaries.

If you wish to serve on this important committee, please email your completed application to Superintendent Luke Biesecker at lbiesecker@arcatasd.org, or mail to Arcata Elementary School District, 1435 Buttermilk Lane, Arcata CA 95521.

If you have any questions about the Committee, please contact District Superintendent Biesecker at (707) 822-0351, ext. 4 or lbiesecker@arcatasd.org for more information.

post_text:
Memorial Day is Monday, May 25!

On Memorial Day, it’s customary to spend time remembering and honoring the countless veterans who have served the United States throughout the country’s history.

Memorial Day commemorates the men and women who died while in the military service of their country, particularly those who died in battle or as a result of wounds sustained in battle. In other words, the purpose of Memorial Day is to memorialize the veterans who made the ultimate sacrifice for their country. We spend time remembering those who lost their lives and could not come home, reflecting on their service and why we have the luxury and freedom that we enjoy today. We might consider how we can support and safeguard their grieving families and loved ones who are left behind.

For more information on Memorial Day history, visit https://www.almanac.com/content/when-memorial-day

The State of California’s new Pandemic-EBT card helps families buy food and groceries!

Have your family’s finances changed due to COVID-19? Did your children receive free or reduced-price meals at school? Are you already receiving CalFresh, Medi-Cal, or Foster Care benefits? You may be eligible for Pandemic-EBT benefits to help feed your children!

Families could receive up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card. Families already receiving CalFresh, Medi-Cal, or Foster Care benefits should get their card in the mail by May 22 (no online application needed). Families whose children received free or reduced-price meals at school, or whose finances decreased due to COVID-19, may be eligible and can apply online starting May 22. THE APPLICATION DEADLINE IS JUNE 30.

For more information and to apply online starting tomorrow, May 22, visit www.ca.p-ebt.org. If you have questions, email PandemicEBT@dss.ca.gov.

Classified School Employee Week is May 17-23!

California officially recognizes the important contributions of classified school employees each May during Classified School Employee Week. Classified employees work as classroom aides, food servers, custodians, office clerks, groundskeepers, one-on-one student aides, bus drivers, and more. Each one is integral to the school environment. They form relationships with students and model teamwork and good citizenship. Students often know classified staff members by name, and look forward to the friendly faces that greet them each day on the bus, in the cafeteria line, and in the hallways.

Thank a Classified School Employee today!

Saturday, May 16 is Armed Forces Day!

Armed Forces Day is a joint celebration of all six branches of the U.S. military: Air Force, Army, Coast Guard, Marine Corps, Navy, and the newly created Space Force. The day honors all people currently serving in the U.S. armed forces. This includes the men and women who have served or are serving in the Army, Navy, Marine Corps, Air Force, Space Force and Coast Guard, including the National Guard and Reserve components.

Read more: https://militarybenefits.info/armed-forces-day/#ixzz6MWmQX8nc

May 13 is California Day of the Teacher!

California’s Day of the Teacher has its roots in the community and is patterned after the celebration of the traditional “El Dia del Maestro,” which is observed in Mexico and Latin America countries.

This year's theme is California Teachers: Inspiring Generations. Many California educators have been providing the quality public education all students deserve for generations. Parents, aunts, uncles, grandparents, children – all come to together to make a difference in the lives of California students.

Social justice artist Ricardo Morales designed this year’s California Day of the Teacher poster.

Thank a teacher today!

https://www.cta.org/for-educators/meet-cta/classroom-teachers/dayoftheteacher

post_text:
National Police Week: May 10-May 16, 2020

In 1962, President Kennedy proclaimed May 15 as National Peace Officers Memorial Day and the calendar week in which May 15 falls, as National Police Week. Established by a joint resolution of Congress in 1962, National Police Week pays special recognition to those law enforcement officers who have lost their lives in the line of duty for the safety and protection of others.

The crisis that the nation and the world is currently facing has resulted in the cancellation of public gatherings in Washington, DC, during National Police Week 2020. This crisis will not deter the honoring the 307 fallen heroes who are being memorialized on the walls of the National Law Enforcement Officers Memorial. On Wednesday, May 13, 2020, at 8:00 pm Eastern, people will march forward in solidarity with a virtual Candlelight Vigil and the reading of the names that can be watched from anywhere in the world.

Thank a police officer today!

https://nleomf.org/programs-events/national-police-week

post_text:
Happy Cinco de Mayo!

The date is observed to commemorate the Mexican Army's victory over the French Empire at the Battle of Puebla, on May 5, 1862, under the leadership of General Ignacio Zaragoza. The victory of the smaller Mexican force against a larger French force was a boost to morale for the Mexicans. More popularly celebrated in the United States than Mexico, the date has become associated with the celebration of Mexican-American culture. These celebrations began in California, where they have been observed annually since 1863.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinco_de_Mayo?scrlybrkr=f82ad336

Mother's Day is next Sunday, May 10. Here are some cards to download and color for mom and grandmom!

Besides coloring, there are other ways to make your card special:

• Print the card on colored cardstock or thick colored paper instead of white paper.
• Color and trim around the image and paste the image on card stock. Hole punch the top of the card and thread a piece a yarn through to make a hanging card.
• Add stickers, glitter, tissue paper, or sequins.
• Add a child's handprint to the inside of the card.
• Include a poem about mothers to the inside of your card.
• Print out, color, and glue Mother's Day clip art to your card.

shared_text:
Sequoia Park Zoo is feeling excited at Sequoia Park Zoo.
April 30 at 11:08 AM · Eureka, CA ·

Take a peek behind the scenes as Zookeepers Lucinda, Danielle & Vanessa install a new bee colony in the Barnyard! Did you know that bees are a vital part of local and global ecosystems? In fact, they are responsible for pollinating 75% of the fruits, nuts & vegetables grown in the United States! Upon the Zoo reopening, stop by the Barnyard and listen for our buzzing friends or see if you can spot the queen in her hive. #sequoiaparkzoo The Association of Zoos and Aquariums #WeAreAZA #bees #bee #queenbee #zoo #humboldt #humboldtcounty #california Sequoia Park Zoo

TOWN HALL MEETING (by telephone) with Senator Mike McGuire TOMORROW, Wednesday, April 29 at 6:30 pm!

Here are the details:

Who: Senator Mike McGuire; Humboldt, Trinity and Del Norte County public health officers, and a University of California physician focused on infectious diseases.

What: Telephone Town Hall to provide the latest updates on our response to the coronavirus.

When: This Wednesday, April 29 at 6:30 p.m.

How to attend: Dial 844-721-7241, enter code 9362370 and follow the prompts. You will be connected to the live town hall via telephone and you will be able to listen to the doctors providing critical updates. Due to system constraints, the town hall is limited to the first 1,000 participants.

How to ask a question and get involved with the Town Hall: Email your questions and comments in advance and in real time to: Senator.McGuire@Senate.ca.gov

post_text:
Happy Arbor Day!

“The creation of a thousand forests is in one acorn.” – Ralph Waldo Emerson

Arbor Day is an annual observance that celebrates the role of trees in our lives and promotes tree planting and care. The tree has appeared throughout history and literature as the symbol of life. The holiday was first observed in 1872 in Nebraska – which was once a treeless plain!

Visit the Arbor Day Foundation website for educational resources and activities, the history of Arbor Day, celebration materials, and more: https://www.arborday.org/celebrate/

KEET-TV wants to hear from you!

KEET is a PBS-member television station located in Eureka. They are accepting short video clips, shot on your phone or tablet, to highlight just what people are doing locally to manage their down time as part of the Shelter-in-Place order. Gardening? Cooking? Knitting? Cat grooming? If it helps you, they want to hear about it. Also, whatever silver linings you've discovered in quarantine.

Keep your videos to under one minute, and feel free to include anyone and everyone in your household. Even in these hard times, KEET wants to help you build a better community. (These short videos will be used on KEET-HD and may be edited for length.)

Send your video files to production@keet-tv.org.

ARCATA SCHOOL DISTRICT SPRING BREAK REMINDER:

Happy Friday ASD Community!
We just want to remind you that our Food Services program will continue to provide meals throughout Spring break. Meals will continue to be provided Monday through Friday at no cost to students or families, regardless of socioeconomic status - parents can pick up meals for their children. Breakfast/lunch meal pickup is available at the following locations:
Arcata Elementary School: 11:00 - 12:00
Sunny Brae Middle School: 11:00 - 12:00

Collection will be happening in Arcata on Thursday, April 2, Monday the 6th, and Wednesday the 8th.

Is it safe to donate blood? YES! And importantly, blood drives are considered essential services. Blood bank staff follow rigorous safety and disinfection protocols at blood drives and donation centers.

Please help if you can! Here are the details: http://www.nccbb.net/index.html

Huffman will be joined by local experts to discuss the response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) and answer questions from viewers. In compliance with Shelter in Place orders, this is not an in-person event. You can participate in the event on Facebook Live at www.facebook.com/RepHuffman/. •William “Bill” Koontz, Public Information Officer, Small Business Administration

post_text: Happy Read Across America Day!
shared_text:
Arcata Elementary School
March 1 at 3:31 PM ·

AES will be celebrating Read Across America on Monday, March 2nd. We have an exciting day planned with have guest readers coming into classrooms.

Read Across America Day, also known as Dr Seuss Day, is a yearly observance in the USA inaugurated by the NEA (National Education Association).

NEA launched the Read Across America, which is an initiative on reading that began in 1997, to encourage children in reading more books and also getting them excited about reading. On March 2, 1998, the first Read Across America Day was celebrated; since then, it has been held annually. The special day mainly focuses on motivating children to read as it improves their performance in school.

Children and families are invited to Family Arts Day at the Morris Graves Museum of Art in Eureka on Saturday, February 8th at 2:00pm! Bring the whole family to celebrate current exhibitions at the Museum through an afternoon of learning, art-making, and exploring your local art museum!

Get inspiration from Avery Palmer’s exhibition “Recurrence: Avery Palmer Returns to Humboldt” and make your own sculpture using modeling clay. We will learn how “Scale”, one of the many principles of design, can alter the meaning and interpretation of a sculpture. We will use what we learn about scale to change the meaning of our sculpture.

Admission is $5 for adults; $2 for seniors (age 65 and over), military veterans, and students with ID; children 17 and under free; Families with an EBT Card and valid ID receive free admission through the Museums for All initiative, Museum members are free.

Bird nesting season has begun! The City of Arcata reminds residents that Humboldt Bay and its surrounding areas are home to a wide variety of bird species, so it is especially important that all community members check for active nests before trimming or removing vegetation during nesting season. Tuesday, September 1, 2020 through Sunday, January 31, 2021, is the best time to plan for tree removal, invasive plant species management, mowing, and brush clearing.

For more information, visit https://www.cityofarcata.org/civicalerts.aspx?AID=336

post_text:
Fred Korematsu Day - Thursday, January 30 at the Humboldt State University Library!

Fred Korematsu, a California native, became a civil rights champion when he refused to obey Executive Order 9066, which sent 120,000 Americans of Japanese ancestry into internment camps.

HSU will observe the annual Fred Korematsu Day of Civil Liberties and the Constitution with a documentary film followed by a discussion of the history on Japanese American World War II internment camps.

For more information, visit https://library.humboldt.edu/node/1182

Concerned about climate change? Chris Peters, a traditional Yurok/Karuk man who has spent the last 45 years working to revitalize Yurok culture and ceremony, will hold a presentation this Sunday, January 26 at the Humboldt Unitarian Universalist Fellowship on the climate crisis and how traditional ecological knowledge may offer a pathway to recovery. Presentations are at 9:00 and 11:00 am.Childcare provided!

For more information, call (707) 822-3793, or visit https://www.northcoastjournal.com/humboldt/yurok-wisdom-for-a-changing-world/Event?oid=16249700

NOTICE OF PUBLIC HEARING ON JANUARY 13:
The Arcata School District Board of Education will hold a public hearing and take action on whether to transition the District to trustee-area voting, and establish trustee-area voting districts. The purpose of this hearing is to review the maps of the proposed trustee areas and receive feedback from the public. Please join us on Monday, January 13 at the Sunny Brae Middle School Multipurpose Room at 6:30 pm!

The public hearing notice (in English and Spanish) and proposed trustee-area maps are available for review at the District Office (1435 Buttermilk Lane), the Sunny Brae Middle School Office (1430 Buttermilk Lane), and the Arcata Elementary School Office (2400 Baldwin Street). These documents can also be found on the ASD website (link on the homepage under Latest News).

For more information, please call the District Office at (707) 822-0351, extension 4.

post_text: Many congratulations to Eleanor and Savanna!
shared_text:
Arcata Elementary School is with Jeffrey Abell.
December 18, 2019 at 3:17 PM ·

Every year, the National Geographic Society sponsors a geography contest called The National Geographic Bee, and students in the fourth through eighth grades compete to see whose geographic knowledge will reign supreme.

The 4th and 5th grade competitors practiced at their recess, at home, and on the bus, to prepare for the big event. Many thanks to Mrs. Adams for coordinating the event, and Mrs. Yeoman, our presenter, did a terrific job with the pronunciation of places near and far.

This year our first place winner is fourth grade student, Eleanor, and our second place winner is Savanna. All of the students did a fabulous job.
